{"title_page": "Premier League records and statistics", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n\n{{for|the all time English league statistics|Football records and statistics in England}}\n\nThe top tier of [[Football in England|English football]] was renamed the [[Premier League]] for the start of the [[1992\u201393 in English football|1992\u201393 season]]. The following page details the football records and statistics of the Premier League.\n\n==League records==\n\n\n===Titles===\n*Most titles: 13,<!-- Premier League ONLY do not change to 20 --> [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]<ref name=\"WinnerList\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engchamp.html#c1993|title=England \u2013 List of Champions|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|date=26 September 2014|accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref>\n*Most consecutive title wins: 3\n**[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] ([[1998\u201399 FA Premier League|1998\u201399]], [[1999\u20132000 FA Premier League|1999\u20132000]], [[2000\u201301 FA Premier League|2000\u201301]])<ref name=\"WinnerList\"/>\n**[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] ([[2006\u201307 FA Premier League|2006\u201307]], [[2007\u201308 Premier League|2007\u201308]], [[2008\u201309 Premier League|2008\u201309]])<ref name=\"WinnerList\"/>\n*Biggest title-winning margin: 19 points, [[2017\u201318 Premier League|2017\u201318]]; [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] (100 points) over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] (81 points)<ref name=\"cityrecords3\">{{cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/15126/11371144/which-records-have-manchester-city-broken-this-season|title=Which records have Manchester City broken this season?|date=14 May 2018|accessdate=17 May 2018|website=Sky Sports}}</ref>\n*Smallest title-winning margin: 0 points and +8 [[goal difference]] \u2013 [[2011\u201312 Premier League|2011\u201312]]; [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] (+64) over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] (+56). Both finished on 89 points, but Manchester City won the title with a superior goal difference \u2013 the only time that goal difference has decided the Premier League title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/news/news/2011-12/may/manchester-city-win-barclays-premier-league.html|title=Manchester City win Barclays Premier League title|website=premierleague.com|date=13 May 2012|accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref>\n* Winning a title with most remaining games: 5 games<ref>{{cite news|title=Which records have Man City broken?|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/666355|publisher=Premier League|date=13 May 2018|accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref>\n** [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] ([[2000\u201301 FA Premier League|2000\u201301]])\n** [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] ([[2017\u201318 Premier League|2017\u201318]])\n\n===Points===\n* Most points in a season: 100, [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] ([[2017\u201318 Premier League#League table|2017\u201318]])<ref name=\"cityrecords3\"/>\n* Most points over 38 consecutive Premier League games: 110, [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] ([[2018\u201319 Premier League#League table|2018\u201319]] to [[2019\u201320 Premier League#League table|2019\u201320]])<ref>{{cite web |title=Liverpool match 18 game winning record with fightback: LFC 3-2 West Ham |url=https://www.anfield-online.co.uk/match-reports/premiership/2020/liverpool-match-18-game-winning-record-with-fightback-lfc-3-2-west-ham/|website=Anfield Online|accessdate=24 February 2020 |date=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n* Biggest lead at any point in a season: 25, [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] ([[2019\u201320 Premier League#League table|2019\u201320]])<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/1561869|title=Which Premier League records can Liverpool break?|date=25 February 2020|website=premierleague.com|publisher=Premier League|accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n* 